title: For Sale:  WWII Winchester M1 Garand
postcontent: Model: M1 GarandYear of Manufacture: January, 1945 (page 173 of Joe Poyer’s "M1 GARAND 1936 to 1957" 3rd edition) Barrel Date: December, 1950Caliber: .30-06 SpringfieldAction Type: Semi-Automatic with En Bloc Clip Fed Internal MagazineMarkings: There is no visible import mark. The gas tube screw is marked with a “HRM”. (page 80 of Joe Poyer’s "M1 GARAND 1936 to 1957" 3rd edition)Barrel Length: Approximately 24"Sights / Optics: The front sight is a blade set between two protective ears. The rear sight is a fully adjustable aperture. The windage knob is marked “LEFT arrow” twice and “DRC”. The elevation knob is marked from “2-12” in increments of 2 and “”WC E”.Stock Configuration & Condition: The three piece hardwood stock has a pistol grip, metal nosecaps, a stacking loop, two sling loops and a metal buttplate with hinged door for storage in the butt. The front of the grip is marked with a circled "P”. The bottom of the grip is marked “R” and “5051”. The left side of the forearm shows a deep scrape that has removed an area of surface wood. The remainder of the wood shows scrapes, scratches and compression marks. Some of these are deep. The LOP measures 13 1/8" from the front of the trigger to the back of the buttplate. The stocks rate in about Very Good overall condition.Type of Finish: ParkerizedFinish Originality: RefinishedBore Condition: The lands are bright and grooves are dark. The rifling is deep. There is erosion in the grooves. The bore shows an M.E. of 4. The throat shows a T.E. of 5.5.Overall Condition: This rifle retains about 83% of its current metal finish. The barrel and gas tube nut show scrapes, scratches and thinning of the finish. The rest of the metal shows various light scrapes, small scratches and thinning on the leading edges of the metal. The buttplate is worn. The screw heads are intact. The markings are faded. Overall, this rifle rates in about Very Good condition, as refinished.Mechanics: The action functions correctly. We have not fired this rifle.Box, Paperwork& Accessories: The rifle comes with an owner’s manual and paperwork from the Civilian Marksmanship Program (CMP). The CMP Certificate of Authenticity has the rifle's serial number on it as well as the CMP seal. The previous owner of the rifle has cut out the name following the “Was Sold To:” line. The certificate is in about Very Good to Fine condition. The manual and two other CMP cards are in about Fine condition.Our Assessment: This Winchester M1 Garand rifle was originally made back in 1945. It has since been refinished and rebuilt, but it still has its WWII dated receiver. It is in Very Good condition and should provide someone with hard hitting fun on the range. Here is some information on the rifle from http://www.scott-duff.com/WhoHowManyWhen.htm: “The first production M1 was successfully proof fired, function fired, and fired for accuracy on 21 July 1937. Thus began manufacture of what was to become the greatest production effort in the long history of Springfield Armory…The Winchester Repeating Arms Company of New Haven, Connecticut was the only other World War II era producer of M1 rifles. Winchester received an Educational Order on 4 April 1939 to produce 500 M1s. The first one hundred rifles, under that Order, were shipped on 27 December 1940. On 20 September 1939, Winchester received its first of many production contracts for additional rifles. Government records indicate Winchester delivered 513,880 M1 rifles between December 1940 and June 1945. The surrender of Germany in May 1945 resulted in termination of M1 rifle manufacture at Winchester as of 30 June 1945. title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith and Wesson Mark II Hand Ejector (45 LC)
postcontent:
This is a Smith & Wesson .455 (re-chambered for 45 LC) Mark II hand Ejector 2nd Model, and has British proof marks with all matching numbers, with 6.5" barrel.  This pistol was equipped with a RARE front bead sight. Normally the bead front sight was reserved for target models, but some were equipped based on availability of parts, as these were manufactured during war time. Serial #318xxx Bore looks good, no pitting anywhere and rifling’s are defined. This Smith and Wesson is in excellent condition for a gun that is 100 years old. Just a real treasure to have.  ------------------------ Some History:
Production of the .455 Mark II Hand Ejector Second Model began in 1915 and continued until 1917 with serial numbers following on from the First model starting at serial number 5001 and continuing on up to serial number 74755. Although for various reasons, as stated previously, there are some Mark I's numbered in the early part of this serial number range including those made by the using up of old parts. In total there were 69,754 Mark II .455's produced.
 
The Canadian Government purchased 14,500 directly from Smith & Wesson and in addition 1,105 were made for the commercial market after completion of the British contract. The rest went to the British Government.
When these guns were sold off as War surplus some were converted to more popular calibers due to the unavailability of the .455 ammunition, especially those that went to the United States. The two usual conversions were to .45 long Colt by lengthening the chambers and then either the cylinder was shortened or some metal was removed from the recoil shield to allow for the extra thickness of the rim on the cartridge case. The other conversion was to .45 ACP by shortening the cylinder and using .45 ACP in half moon clips or .45 auto rim ammunition.
-------------------------- Just a beautiful, and perfect shooting gun. Very accurate, a must have for any Smith and Wesson collection. All transactions are face to face in the Tulsa area. Prefer text or email. nine18-four02-zero854
